SIMPLE: stint
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stint
<hw>Stint</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any one of several species of small sandpipers, as the
sanderling of Europe and America, the dunlin, the little stint of India
(<spn>Tringa minuta</spn>), etc. Called also
<altname>pume</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A phalarope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stint
<hw>Stint</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stinted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stinting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>stinten</ets>,
<ets>stenten</ets>, <ets>stunten</ets>, to cause to cease, AS.
<ets>styntan</ets> (in comp.) to blunt, dull, fr. <ets>stunt</ets> dull,
stupid; akin to Icel. <ets>stytta</ets> to shorten, <ets>stuttr</ets>
short, dial, Sw. <ets>stynta</ets> to shorten, <ets>stunt</ets> short.
Cf. <er>Stent</er>, <er>Stunt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To restrain
within certain limits; to bound; to confine; to restrain; to restrict to
a scant allowance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall not go about to extenuate the latitude of the curse upon
the earth, or <qex>stint</qex> it only to the production of weeds.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>stints</qex> them in their meals.</q>
<rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put an end to; to stop.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To assign a certain (<it>i. e.</it>, limited) task
to (a person), upon the performance of which one is excused from further
labor for the day or for a certain time; to stent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To serve successfully; to get with foal; -- said of
mares.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The majority of maiden mares will become <qex>stinted</qex> while
at work.</q> <rj><qau>J. H. Walsh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stint
<hw>Stint</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To stop; to cease.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They can not <qex>stint</qex> till no thing be left.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>stint</qex> thou too, I pray thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The damsel <qex>stinted</qex> in her song.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 2. to be parsimonious in expending some resource; -- used with
"on" to indicate the item conserved. "Don't stint on the potatos!"
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stint
<hw>Stint</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Also written <ets>stent</ets>. See
<er>Stint</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Limit; bound;
restraint; extent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God has wrote upon no created thing the utmost <qex>stint</qex> of
his power.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Quantity or task assigned; proportion
allotted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His old <qex>stint</qex> -- three thousand pounds a year.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 3. A period of work at a specific task; as, to do one's stint in
the army, an actor who did a stint as a cab driver. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stintance</ent>⟦br⟧
